DG is recapturing a respectable and solid comp and EPS algorithm which we believe is largely reflected in its \(\sim 18x\) NTM P/E multiple. At this level, EPS upside potential from shrink and operational improvements is balanced by risk that top- line growth levels off. DG's top- line is recovering from \(\sim 2\) years of below- average growth, and strong Q2'25 gross margin performance (+137 bps y/y) driven by improvements in shrink, inventory markups, and damages is an encouraging sign. Comp and EPS guidance for 25 is achievable \(\sim 24\%\) and \(\) 6.05\(at the midpoint, respectively), and we think the bull case presents meaningful upside as a return to algo comps (+2%- 3%) while also making progress toward a \(\sim 6\%\) EBIT margin largely through gross margin expansion yields mid- to- high teens % EPS growth in 26/27. While no layup, achieving a \(\sim 6\%\) EBIT margin would be driven by a combination of 1) lower shrink (\~80 bps), 2) lower damages (\~40 bps), and 3) DG Media (up to \~150 bps), though the advertising tailwind would likely be realized on a 3- 5 year timeframe rather than near- term. On the other hand, comps in 25 are benefitting from both easier y/y compares and competitor closures / share loss, which creates a more challenging set for top- line growth in 26. Further, SG&A deleverage could persist as wage inflation, store investments, and repair & maintenance costs continue to rise. Combined with the uncertainty of how consumers may respond to tariff- induced inflation in 2H25, this offsets the potential upside, in our view.

How do 2Q25 results shape our view? We are Overweight rated. Risk/reward is positive with \(\sim 40\% / \sim 30\%\) upside/downside to our bull/bear cases and \(\sim 9\%\) upside to our raised \(\) 600\(PT. We think valuation of \(\sim 21x\) NTM P/E (a \(\sim 15\%\) discount to ULTA's long- term average of \(\sim 25x\) ) is undemanding for a business with renewed topline momentum and market share gains. ULTA's Unleashed plan continues to drive solid results, as evidenced by 2Q25 comps of \(+6.7\%\) (vs. the Street at \(+2.9\%\) ) and raised '25 comp guidance to \(\sim 3\%\) at the midpoint (vs. \(+0.8\%\) prior). We think there is room for upside to the 2H25 comp guide of \(\sim\) flat to +low- single- digits given the industry's stable backdrop and minimal tariff risk, and model \(\sim 4\%\) comps in 2H25 accordingly. One knock on the quarter is that SG&A spend is expected to step up in 2H25, with '25 SG&A dollars increasing \(\sim 13 - 14\%\) y/y (vs. \(\sim 10\%\) prior, driven by higher incentive comp, investments, increased advertising, and the addition of Space NK). However, we think this level of investment is one- time in nature and will drive continued share gains for ULTA into '26 and beyond.

How our estimates are changing. We are raising our PT to \(\) 600\(from\) \ \(550\) , based on \(\sim 20x\) P/E our '27 EPS of \(\sim\) 30.34 (vs. \(\sim 21x\) our '26 EPS prior). We are rolling forward our valuation to '27 estimates but maintaining our underlying methodology. We are raising our '25/26/27 EPS estimates by \(\sim 6\% / - 3\% - 2\%\) to \(\sim\) \(24.55 / \sim\) 27.09/ \(\sim\) 30.34. In '25, we model comps of \(+4\%\) and \(\sim 185\) bps of EBIT margin contraction. Alongside \(\sim\) 900m in buybacks and a \(\sim 24.5\%\) tax rate (per guidance), this produces '25 EPS of \(\sim\) 24.55. In '26/27, we model comps of \(+3.2\%\) \(+4\%\) , EBIT margin of \(\sim 12.2\% / \sim 12.4\%\) and EPS of \(\sim\) 27.09/ \(\sim\) 30.34. A \(\sim 20x\) multiple is above current valuation at \(\sim 18x\) FY3 P/E, which we think is fair given ULTA's solid execution in its Unleashed plan continues to drive share gains.

How do 2Q25 results shape our view? We remain OW- rated and raise our PT to \(\) 253\(, implying 18\%\) upside vs the current stock price. We believe DKS is undervalued given its growth potential and 2) durability as a share gainer in the attractive sporting goods retail ecosystem. We view the cautiousness embedded in 2H25e guidance as conservatism and prudence given impending tariffs and believe the core tenets of our investment thesis of steady comp growth and margin expansion are intact. DKS' low teens (14x) P/E multiple is attractive relative to a group of high quality Hardline/Broadline retailers.

DKS's 6th quarter in a row with \(>4\%\) comp sales growth underscores the power of its value proposition as an ecosystem- combining experiential retail (House of Sport' format), omnichannel shopping, expanding GameChanger subscriber base,

retail media and inroads in sports technology- in driving market share gains and profitability over time. While the FL acquisition adds a level of complexity to the story, DKS' strategy of pursuing both organic and growth has been successful, in the aggregate, over the long term. Tepid implied 2H25e guidance (providing for comps of \(+1\%\) at the midpoint), and headwinds to gross margin from mounting tariff pressures, are likely to keep valuation range bound near- term. All considered, we believe DKS will continue to take market share as it leverages best- in- class customer experience, digital ecosystem, and deepening relationships with key brand partners, offering compelling value at the current \(13.4\times 27\mathrm{eP / E}\) valuation.

By the numbers. 2Q25 comps's acceleration to \(+5.0\%\) (vs Street at \(+3.2\%\) ), along with gross margin expansion of 33bps (including a 18bps contribution from higher merchandise margins), speaks to improving quality of DKS assortment allocations, even lapping the merchandise margin step- up in 2Q24. SG&A rate deleverage of 106bps, largely due to ongoing investments in technology - i.e. GameChanger, retail media - and store experience, put adjusted operating margin at \(13.0\%\) (down 80bps y/y, vs consensus' \(12.7\%\) ) and adjusted EPS at \(4.38\) vs the Street's \(4.28\) estimate.

Implied 2H25e guidance strikes a cautious tone, factoring in comparable stores sales of \(- 0.6\%\) to \(+2.3\%\) (likely reflecting a measure of conservatism, as there's no sign of consumer slowdown to date), and an adjusted operating margin range of \(9.6\%\) to \(10.3\%\) , compared to \(9.8\%\) in 2H24 and consensus' \(9.9\%\) . Still, both merchandise and gross margin are expected to expand in 2H25e. While adjusted operating margin is still expected to remain flat y/y at \(11.1\%\) on a FY'25e basis, the shape of the P&L is likely to be less reliant on gross margin expansion - which we estimate at \(\sim 40\) bps for the FY'25e, vs 75bps previously, given rising tariff cost headwinds - and more dependent on a less onerous SG&A rate development, given sustained upside surprise in comps.

How do 2Q25 results shape our view? We are Equal- weight rated and risk/reward is balanced with \(\sim 40\%\) upside/downside to our bull/bear cases and \(\sim 6\%\) upside to our unchanged \(\) 75\(PT. Our view is unchanged; valuation of\) \sim 1x\(NTM P/E (vs. its long - term \sim 12.5x average) screens fair as upside from here needs sustainable - low- single- digit growth, which we think will be a challenge in this environment given competitive pressures. BBY's efforts to re- engage the consumer, including improving the in- store experience and leveraging vendor partnerships, alongside strong product launches (i.e. the Nintendo Switch 2 in June), continue to drive category growth (2Q25 enterprise comps of \(+1.6\%\) beat the Street at \(- 0.4\%\) and 3QTD is in the \~low- single- digits). That said, we see limited EBIT margin expansion from here as the product cycle in higher- margin categories has yet to turn, and BBY may require further investments to drive higher demand. In addition, profitability drivers such as

execution and profitability improvements are balanced by continued negative- to- flat comps which could persist into early '26, in our view. The upside case is shaped by a top- line acceleration driven by "Phase 3" investments yielding a return to market share gains and stronger customer retention, while EBITDA margins continue to expand as WOOF prioritizes its retail execution efforts (i.e., disciplined promotions, enhanced customer experience, and price management). This momentum could drive \(\sim 40 - 50\) bps of EBITDA margin expansion in '26/27 in the bull case, yielding \(\sim 10\%\) EBITDA growth in each year. However, with comps declining LSD% for the second consecutive quarter and expected to decline similarly in Q325, we see risk of an elongated comp slump in which the benefits from "Phase 3" investments take longer to materialize. While EBITDA margins can still expand in '25/26 due to WOOF's initiatives, an elongated top- line recovery likely limits EBITDA growth to \(+\) MSD% in '26/27. In addition, with the impact of tariffs slated to accelerate through the balance of the year, implied Q425 EBITDA guidance yields - flat growth y/y vs. double- digit growth in the prior quarters. Given an uncertain tariff and macro backdrop, there is risk the cost pressures continue into '26 and further limit EBITDA growth. Longer term, the Pet category is durable with sustainable growth drivers, and we believe there is a place for retailers like WOOF to succeed at taking share when supported by a clearly defined value proposition.

Continued Share Gainer In A Growing Category
We are Overweight rated ULTA given its ability to gain share in an attractive, durable Beauty category.

Sales momentum and margin levels can hold in the near- to medium- term post- Covid (+LSD comps/ \(\sim 12\%\) + EBIT margins) against a continued growing Beauty category, strong loyalty customer base, and solid digitization efforts to drive guest engagement. Valuation at \~high- teens NTM P/E screens inexpensive in our view, and there is room for additional upside as expectations are reasonable, if not a bit low. If ULTA continues to gain share and focuses on initiatives to drive profitability, this may unlock higher value for the stock.

Macro Headwinds With Closeout / Trade Down Upside
